    "description": "FEA predicts construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement for the non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw design under ASTM F1717 static compression-bending. Validated by direct comparison to bench testing (N=11 constructs across two laboratories). Model influence MEDIUM (testing confirms results); decision consequence MEDIUM (pedicle screw fracture leads to revision surgery, not death).",
    "intendedUse": "Demonstrate that the FEA modeling framework reproduces experimental compression-bending behavior of a non-cannulated pedicle screw construct within pre-established acceptance bounds (<10% QoI difference, E/uval < 1.96).",
    "modelInfluence": "Medium",
    "decisionConsequence": "Medium",
    "deviceClass": "Class II",
    "hasApplicabilityConstraint": {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/cou/cou1-noncannulated/applicability",
      "type": "ApplicabilityConstraint",
      "name": "Applicability constraint: non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw, ASTM F1717 static loading",
      "description": "Model applicability is restricted to non-cannulated titanium-alloy pedicle screws with nominal outer diameter 7.5 mm and thread pitch 3.0 mm, tested or simulated under quasi-static ASTM F1717 compression-bending protocol. Results are not transferable to cannulated variants, screws outside the 6.5–8.5 mm diameter range, or dynamic/fatigue loading regimes without separate validation."
    },
    "hasOperatingEnvelope": {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/cou/cou1-noncannulated/envelope",
      "type": "OperatingEnvelope",
      "name": "Operating envelope: ASTM F1717 quasi-static compression-bending",
      "description": "Applied compressive load: 0–3500 N; crosshead displacement rate: 5 mm/min ± 0.5 mm/min; test block separation: 44 mm ± 1 mm; ambient temperature: 23 °C ± 2 °C; relative humidity: 50 % ± 10 %; screw insertion angle: 0° (parallel to rod axis); rod diameter: 5.5 mm cobalt-chromium; specimen lot hardness: 32–36 HRC. FEA boundary conditions reproduce these bounds exactly; extrapolation outside these ranges is not supported by the current validation evidence."
    }
  },
  "hasSensitivityAnalysis": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/sensitivity/cou1-noncannulated",
    "type": "SensitivityAnalysis",
    "name": "One-at-a-time sensitivity analysis on titanium elastic modulus, friction coefficient, and thread-block contact stiffness",
    "description": "Elastic modulus of the Ti-6Al-4V screw was varied ±10 % about the nominal 114 GPa; yield force QoI changed by ±4.2 %, confirming moderate sensitivity. Thread-to-block contact friction coefficient was swept from 0.10 to 0.30 (nominal 0.18); stiffness QoI varied by ±6.8 %, the largest single-parameter effect, driving the uncertainty budget. Rod-screw interface contact stiffness penalty factor was varied over one order of magnitude; displacement at 40 mm force changed by less than 1.5 %, indicating low sensitivity. These results informed the uncertainty quantification bounds reported in each ValidationResult and confirmed that the dominant uncertainty source is contact friction, which was subsequently bounded by coupon-level friction measurements."
  },
